ructures. Both then and now, the Métis have engaged in political action to negotiate their place alongside federal and provincial partners in Confederation. As Canada engages in nation-to-nation relationships to advance reconciliation, this book provides timely insight into the Métis Nation’s ongoing struggle to remain a free and self-governing Indigenous people.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMétisxPolitics and government. 0aMétisxPolitics and government. 0aRacially mixed peoplexPolitics and government. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Indigenous Studies.2bisacsh1 aChartier, Clément, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDubois, Janique, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMadden, Jason, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311127268908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2019z978311127498008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311141772140uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077486077240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774860772423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774860772/original  a978-3-11-127268-9  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  a978-3-11-127498-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2019b2019  a978-3-11-141772-1  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles